<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  A4-079: production network-security policy. Capacitor's default
  template ships this file with cleartext-localhost / 10.0.2.2
  exemptions intended for `cap run` against a dev server, but the
  same exemption shipped to production lets a malicious app on the
  same device run an HTTP listener on localhost and intercept any
  webview request that hits a localhost URL. Combined with the CORS
  allowlist already removing `http://localhost` (audit A2-1009 in
  apps/backend/src/middleware/cors.ts), production user impact is
  bounded — but the exemption is one buggy code path away from
  exploitable.

  Production posture: NO cleartext exemption. Android API 28+
  defaults `cleartextTrafficPermitted` to false, so the network-
  security config can simply omit any cleartext domain-config and
  rely on the OS default. HTTPS-only across every webview request.

  Local development against a cleartext localhost backend is a
  separate concern. If a dev needs the exemption, swap in a
  `src/debug/res/xml/network_security_config.xml` Gradle build
  variant locally — that variant overrides `src/main` only for the
  `debug` build type, so release / store builds remain strict.

  The overlay script copies this file on every `cap sync` so
  Capacitor's permissive default doesn't return.
-->
<network-security-config>
    <!-- Empty: defaults apply (HTTPS required, no cleartext). -->

    <!--
      FE-04 / ADR-027 — TLS certificate pinning for api.loopfinance.io.

      DELIBERATELY INERT. ADR-027 (§"SSL / cert pinning") accepts a
      Phase-1 DEFERRAL of pinning: TLS rides the system trust store +
      Fly's edge cert today. The Phase-2 trigger is "first confirmed
      MITM event in production telemetry OR enterprise customer
      requirement" — neither has fired (re-accepted 2026-06-16). So the
      <pin-set> below is left COMMENTED OUT: an active <pin-set> with a
      wrong or placeholder digest bricks EVERY API call the instant the
      pinned cert rotates, which for a money app is a self-inflicted
      outage. This block is a ready-to-activate recipe, not a live
      control.

      Activation is an ADR-027 Phase-2 decision (get sign-off first).
      To activate:
        1. Compute the base64 SHA-256 of the SubjectPublicKeyInfo for
           the pin target. Per ADR-027 §"Phase-2 implementation order",
           pin the Fly / CDN *intermediate CA* SPKI, NOT the leaf —
           leaves rotate on a ~90-day Let's Encrypt/edge cadence and
           would force an app release every rotation. Intermediates
           rotate on a known, multi-year cadence.
             openssl s_client -connect api.loopfinance.io:443 -showcerts </dev/null \
               | openssl x509 -pubkey -noout \
               | openssl pkey -pubin -outform der \
               | openssl dgst -sha256 -binary | openssl enc -base64
           (run once per cert in the chain to pick the intermediate).
        2. ALWAYS ship a BACKUP pin — a second <pin> for the next
           intermediate / a KMS-held backup key CSR — so a planned
           rotation doesn't require an app-store round-trip. A pin-set
           with a single pin is an outage waiting for a rotation.
        3. Set expiration ~90 days out and wire a calendar reminder to
           refresh before it lapses; an expired pin-set falls back to
           system trust (fails OPEN, by Android design) — safer than a
           hard brick but it silently disables the control, so treat
           the expiry as a deadline, not a safety net.
        4. Also implement the iOS side (no network_security_config
           equivalent): URLSessionDelegate SPKI pinning or TrustKit in
           a small Capacitor plugin. Capacitor's WKWebView traffic does
           NOT flow through URLSession, so iOS pinning only covers the
           app-client `fetch()` path unless the WebView is also
           intercepted — a Phase-2 native spike (see handoff doc FE-04).
        5. Verify on-device with an mitmproxy + user-installed root CA:
           BEFORE = requests succeed through the proxy (MITM works);
           AFTER = requests fail (pin rejects the proxy's cert). See
           docs/audit/audit-2026-07/native-device-qa-handoff.md FE-04.

      <domain-config>
          <domain includeSubdomains="false">api.loopfinance.io</domain>
          <pin-set expiration="2026-10-15">
              <!-- Primary: Fly/CDN INTERMEDIATE CA SPKI (replace). -->
              <pin digest="SHA-256">REPLACE_WITH_INTERMEDIATE_SPKI_SHA256_BASE64=</pin>
              <!-- Backup: next intermediate / held backup key (replace). -->
              <pin digest="SHA-256">REPLACE_WITH_BACKUP_SPKI_SHA256_BASE64=</pin>
          </pin-set>
      </domain-config>
    -->
</network-security-config>
